{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:55:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13892"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583806"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:29:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:29:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13892"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13892"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.89,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6511"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57003"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17253"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of progressive breathlessness and coughing up blood. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and continues to smoke. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with plethoric facies. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. You note right-sided ptosis and miosis (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following describes the pathophysiology of the sign shown?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Compression of the facial nerve at the stylomastoid foramen","Disruption of parasympathetic fibres in the oculomotor nerve","Interruption of sympathetic chain by apical lung tumour","Infiltration of the trigeminal nerve at the cavernous sinus","Compression of the trochlear nerve at the superior orbital fissure"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests an underlying lung malignancy. The combination of coughing up blood, breathlessness, significant smoking history, and Horner\u0027s syndrome in a man of this age is highly concerning for a superior sulcus (Pancoast) tumour. Urgent chest imaging with CT would be indicated to confirm the diagnosis and stage the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows Horner\u0027s syndrome, characterised by ipsilateral ptosis and miosis. This occurs due to \u003Cstrong\u003Einterruption of sympathetic chain by apical lung tumour\u003C/strong\u003E. The sympathetic pathway to the eye consists of a three-neuron chain: first-order neurons from the hypothalamus to the spinal cord, second-order neurons from the spinal cord to the superior cervical ganglion, and third-order neurons from the ganglion to the eye. Disruption anywhere along this pathway results in Horner\u0027s syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompression of the facial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E would cause ipsilateral facial weakness affecting all facial muscles, not isolated ptosis. The facial nerve does not control pupillary function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of parasympathetic fibres in the oculomotor nerve\u003C/strong\u003E would cause pupillary dilation (mydriasis) rather than constriction (miosis), along with complete ptosis and other eye movement abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfiltration of the trigeminal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E would primarily cause sensory changes in the face and would not affect pupil size or eyelid position.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompression of the trochlear nerve\u003C/strong\u003E would cause vertical diplopia due to superior oblique muscle weakness but would not affect pupil size or eyelid position.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the apical lung tumour (Pancoast tumour) is compressing the sympathetic chain in the upper thorax, leading to the classic triad of Horner\u0027s syndrome: ptosis (due to paralysis of M\u00fcller\u0027s muscle), miosis (due to unopposed parasympathetic action on the pupil), and anhidrosis (decreased sweating) on the affected side.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Horner\u0027s syndrome consists of ipsilateral ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis due to disruption of sympathetic innervation.","Apical lung tumours (Pancoast tumours) commonly cause Horner\u0027s syndrome by compressing the sympathetic chain.","The sympathetic pathway to the eye involves a three-neuron chain from hypothalamus to spinal cord to superior cervical ganglion.","Haemoptysis with smoking history in an older adult should raise suspicion for lung cancer."],"references":["National Institute for Health and Care Excellence. Lung cancer: diagnosis and management (NICE Guideline NG122). 2019. Available at: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng122","Davagnanam I, Fraser CL, Miszkiel K, Daniel CS, Plant GT. Adult Horner\u2019s syndrome: a combined clinical, pharmacological, and imaging algorithm. Eye. 2013 Mar;27(3):291\u20138."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57003"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13892"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20831"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20831"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ys6gqD31i2J0DOQDwTohjpEnKNbbGU.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ys6gqD31i2J0DOQDwTohjpEnKNbbGU.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57003"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T19:32:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T19:36:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6511"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71494"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":